#################################################################################################


1. **Remove stopped containers**:
    Removing a stopped container does not affect the associated image. You can still use the image to 
    create new containers.

        docker container prune


2. **Remove unused images**: 
    This will remove all dangling images (i.e., images that are not tagged and not associated with any container)
    Removing an image will not affect existing containers created from that image.

        docker image prune
        docker image prune -a  # To remove all unused images

    
3. **Remove unused volumes**: 
    This will remove all volumes that are not associated with any container

        docker volume prune

4. **Remove unused networks**: 
    This will remove all networks that are not associated with any container

        docker network prune

5. **Clean up everything**: 
    (i.e., remove all stopped containers, unused images, unused volumes, and unused networks), 
    use the `docker system prune` command. To remove all unused images (not just dangling ones), use the `-a` flag

        docker system prune
        docker system prune -a  # To remove all unused images
